column168: ON 04/01/04, A TRANSFORMER WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING ON AN ONYX TRUCK WHILE PARKED AT AN ONYX TEN-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY IN MENOMONEE FALLS, WI AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 PM.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRANSFORMER WAS LEAKING THROUGH THE TOP COVER SEAL.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRUCK WAS DECONNED USING DIESEL FUEL.  THE WOODEN FLOOR SECTIONS OF THE TRUCK WERE REMOVED AND SENT TO A TSCA INCINERATOR ALONG WITH WIPES GENERATED DURING THE CLEAN-UP.  THE CONCENTRATION OF PCBS'S IN THE OIL THAT SPILLED WAS 180 PPM.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS INSPECTED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT AND NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED BUT APPARENTLY THE TOP OF THE TRANSFORMER WAS NOT SEALED PROPERLY.  IN THE FUTURE, TRANFORMER VALVES AND FITTINGS WILL BE INSPECTED FOR LEAKS AND TIGHTNESS PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RICE YARD IN WAYCROSS, GA REPORTED GATX16950, LOAD CAUSTIC ALKALI LIQUID, NOS (SODIUM HYDROXIDE/CRESYLIC ACID) TO BE DRIPPING FROM A PIPE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK BECAUSE THE PIPE CAP WAS NOT APPLIED.  THE TRAINMASTER PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP.  HE ESTIMATED THE LEAK RATE TO BE ABOUT 1 DROP EVERY 5 SEC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER, GIANT YORKTOWN INC., WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE CONTRACTOR ADVISED THAT LIQUID WAS DRIPPING FROM ONE OF THE INTERNAL HEATER COIL PIPES BECAUSE THE CAP WAS NOT APPLIED.  THEY CONFIRMED THE LIQUID DRIPPING WAS PRODUCT USING PH PAPER.  THEY INSTALLED THE HEATER COIL PIPE CAP WRENCH TIGHT AND THE DRIP STOPPED.  THE OTHER 3 HEATER COIL CAPS WERE INSPECTED AND MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  IT WAS ESTIMATED ONLY ABOUT 1 PINT OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE CAR AND IT WAS RECOMMENDED THE CAR BE SHOPPED AFTER IT WAS UNLOADED.  THE REP FROM GIANT INDICATED THE CAR BELONGED TO THE CONSIGNEE, MERISOL AND THEY WOULD ADVISE MERISOL OF THE PROBLEM.
#2 HEATING OIL STARTED TO LEAK AROUND THREADS TO SCULLY GAUGE.  THE TANK WAS CLEANED, NO PRODUCT WAS ON THE GROUND AROUND THE 275 GAL TANK NO RUN-OFF INTO STORM DRAINS.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  THE TANK LEVEL GAGE WAS CHECKED TO CONFIRM THERE WAS ENOUGH ROOM FOR THE LOAD.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE CUSTOMER'S EMPLOYEE WAS MONITORING THE TANK LEVEL INDICATION.  PRIOR TO THE TANK LEVEL INSTRUMENT INDICATING THAT THE TANK WAS FULL, PRODUCT STARTED TO OVERFLOW THE TANK INTO THE TANK'S CONTAINMENT DIKE.  APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OVERFLOWED BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD STOP THE UNLOADING PROCESS (SHUT DOWN THE TRAILER UNLOADING PUMP).  THE CUSTOMER DILUTED THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THE CONTAINMENT DIKE WITH WATER.  THE CUSTOMER DISPOSED OF THE DILUTED MATERIAL INTO THEIR FACILITY TREATMENT SYSTEM.  THE OVERFLOW WAS CAUSED BY AN INCORRECT INDICATION FROM THE TANK'S LEVEL INSTRUMENT.  THE LEVEL INSTRUMENT WAS RE-CALIBRATED BY THE CUSTOMER AND THE LEVEL READING CONFIRMED CORRECT.  A LETTER ASKING THE CUSTOMER TO CONSIDER INSTALLING AN INDEPENDENT HIGH LEVEL PROBE AND ALARM TO HELP PREVENT OVERFLOWING THE STORAGE TANK WILL BE PROVIDED.

AT THE TIME THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED.  UBY IMMEDIATELY PLACED THE SHIPMENTS THAT THE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS SPILLED ONTO ON THE DOCK AND, BEGAN TO EXTRACT THE AFFECTED CARDBOARD THAT SURROUNDED SHIPMENT PROS 493-709366, 843-762533, 960-350410, AND 843-762544.  UBY ALSO PLACED THE AFFECTED CARDBOARD SAFELY IN THE OS&D AREA TO AWAIT THE DRYING OF THE CORROSIVE LIQUID THAT SPILLED ONTO THE CARDBOARD.  AS A RESULT OF THIS SPILL A CHEMICAL INCIDENT REPORT WAS DONE AND SENT TO ORIGIN, INTERMEDIATE DESTINATION AS WELL AS FINAL DESTINATION.  IT IS STRONGLY RECOMMENDED THAT ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BE HANDLED WITH THE SAFE AND PROCEDURAL STEPS THAT CON-WAY WESTERN EXPRESS HAS INSTITUTED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE INTERSECTION OF STATE HWY  53 & ALGONQUIN RD IN ROLLING MEADOWS, ILLINOIS, THE PFA SYSTEMS, INC., CARGO TANK UNIT OVERTURNED, DAMAGING THE TANK AND THE TRACTOR.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WAS RELEASED FORM THE CARGO TANK. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO SEEPAGE FROM FITTINGS ON THE CARGO TANK. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL & APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL WERE RELEASED FORM THE TRACTOR.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE SADDLE TANKS & THE OIL-PAN IN THE TRACTOR.  THE ROLLING MEADOWS FIRE DEPT SPRAYED THE ASPHALT WITH WATER TO PREVENT SPARKING & APPLIED ABSORBENT BOOMS TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT TO THE ASPHALT. THE ROLLING MEADOWS FIRE DEPT GENERATED FOUR 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SOLID WASTE.  HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION OF ADDISON, ILLINOIS TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED CARGO TANK TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION NEUTRALIZED THE FREE SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. HAZCHEM PUMPED THE REMAINING DIESEL FUEL FROM THE SADDLE TANKS & USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO COLLECT THE WATER FROM THE ASPHALT.  HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION REMOVED APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS IF LIQUID WASTE FROM THE SITE FOR DISPOSAL.  HAZCHEM  ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION GENERATED FIVE 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SOLID WASTE, WHICH THE TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE FOUR DRUMS GENERATED BY THE ROLLING MEADOWS FIRE DEPT TO THEIR FACILITY IN ADDISON, ILLINOIS FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION. HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATION TRANSPORTED NINE 55-GALLON DRUMS TO POLLUTION CONTROL INDUSTRIES IN EAST CHICAGO, INDIANA FOR DISPOSAL.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE TO ANY OF THE RELEASED MATERIALS WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND STATED HIS PACKERS MUST HAVE MADE A MISTAKE BECAUSE THEY SHIP THIS WITH PROTECTIVE COVERS ON THE TERMINALS.

THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  YARDMASTER NOTIFIED KINDER MORGAN, CARTERET, NJ FACILITY FOR RESPONSE. DRIVER STAGED THE CARGO ON THE CUSTOMERS SCALES FOR LOADING, PROCEEDED TO THE TOP OF THE TANK TO INSTALL THE LOADING LINE AND BEGIN THE LOADING PROCESS.  IN THE PROCESS THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LOADING LINE, AND THE LOADING LINE LIFTED UP AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON THE TOP TRAILER AND DOWN ONTO THE CUSTOMER SCALES.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER AND THE SCALE.  CTL SENT OUT A CREW TO CLEAN UP THE HARDEN SULFUR ON THE TRAILER AND THE CUSTOMERS SCALE.  THE DRIVER WAS REMOVED FROM DISPATCH UNTIL HE COULD BE RE-TRAINED ON PROPER SECUREMENT AND LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING SANTICIZER 160 INTO A CUSTOMER TANK, THE FILL NOZZLE MALFUNCTIONED CAUSING 15-GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO CONCRETE, WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED.  PRODUCT DID NOT REACH WATERWAYS OR DRAINS AND WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE. INITIAL INVESTIGATION PERFORMED ON 4/26/2004 CONCLUDED THAT THE FILL NOZZLE WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY IN THE TANK.  TRAINING HAS BEEN CONDUCTED TO ENSURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

column168: THIS INCIDENT INVOLVED THE OVERFLOW OF MATERIAL FROM THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  THE STORAGE TANK HAD A CAPACITY OF 13,000 GALLONS.  THE CAPACITY GAGE ON THE STORAGE TANK SHOWED 5100 GALLONS.  OUR DRIVER WAS TO DELIVER 4000 GALLONS OF MATERIAL THAT WOULD BE DILUTED WITH 2000 GALLONS OF WATER WHICH WOULD HAVE TAKEN TO STORAGE TANK TO 11,100 GALLONS.  THE STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED WITH APPROXIMATELY 90 GALLONS OF MATERIAL STILL IN THE CARGO TANK.  IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THE STORAGE TANKS CAPACITY GAUGE WAS OFF BY APPROXIMATELY 450 - 500 GALLONS.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA AROUND THE STORAGE TANK AND WAS FLUSHED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S WASTE WATER TREATMENT FACILITY BY THEIR PERSONNEL.  NO OTHER CONSEQUENCES RESULTED FROM THIS INCIDENT.

THE RELEASE WAS WHAT WAS IN THE HOSE.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: AFTER COMPLETING A 10-HOUR BREAK, THE DRIVER WAS PERFORMING A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND FOUND INK LEAKING ON THE GROUND FROM HIS TRAILER.  HEPACO, A HAZMAT CLEAN UP COMPANY, CAME OUT, CLEANED UP THE INK AND TRANSFERRED THE FREIGHT TO A NEW TRAILER FOR TRANSIT.  AFTER EVALUATING THE SITUATION, KEN MOORE WITH HEPACO DETERMINED IT WAS A DRUM FAILURE.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THE TWO DRUMS OF PAINT WERE LOADED NEXT TO A STEEL HOPPER.  THE HOPPER RUBBED A SMALL CRACK IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM ONLY CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF PAINT WHEN SHIPPED AND LOST ONLY 1 TO 2 GALLONS DUE TO THE CRACK IN SIDE.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT ON FOR DELIVERY.
WHILE LOADING DRUM THE FORKLIFT PUNCTURED THE TOP SIDE SECTION OF THE DRUM CAUSING IT TO LOSE APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT ON TO DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: ON TUESDAY, APRIL 6TH AT 1030 HOURS, A CSX TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEE WORKING IN FAYETTEVILLE YARD OBSERVED DODX14281 DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  TRAINMASTER KIRKS WAS CONTACTED AND IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATIONS EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE SHIPPER, TRANSMONTAIGNA, EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER 800-851-8061, TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE RELEASE.  TRAINMASTER KIRKS PLACED A PLASTIC BUCKET UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO COLLECT THE PRODUCT.  HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND.  ON ARRIVAL, HEPACO REPRESENTATIVES FOUND THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT: EXTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE IN THE OPEN POSITION; AND THE PLASTIC BOTTOM OUTLET CAP CRACKED POSSIBLY DUE TO OVERTIGHTENING.  ESTIMATED TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ONE QUART.  IN ADDITION, EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE FOUND LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (NOT APPLIED).  THE TANK CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: THE PAIL THAT LEAKED WAS THE TOP PAIL OF A SMALL PALLET OF LIKE PAILS. WHEN THE SHIPMENT WAS ABOUT TO BE LOADED, AN ODOR WAS NOTICED BY THE LOADER WHO OBSERVED THAT THE TOP PAIL WAS LEAKING ONTO THE PAIL BELOW IT.  THE LOADER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR.  UPON INSPECTING THE PAIL IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE SEAM IN THE SIDE OF THE PAIL. THERE WERE NO PUNCTURES OR OTHER OBVIOUS DAMAGE THAT COULD HAVE CAUSED THIS LEAK.  THE LEAKING PAIL WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AND SOME ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SMALL AMOUNT (APPROX. 8 OUNCES) THAT HAD LEAKED. THE USED ABSORBENT WAS PLACED IN THE CONTAINMENT DRUM WITH THE LEAKING PAIL.

column42: AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED OR AMMONIA SOLUTIONS RELATIVE DENSITY LESS THAN .880 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: SOMEONE OPENED NH3 NURSE TANK VALVE, TANK# 122, WHILE ATTEMPTING TO STEAL IT.  HE LEFT VALVE OPEN, CAUSING LEAK.  MCPHERSON COUNTY HAZ RESPONSE RESPONDED.  THEY CLOSED VALVE & DISPERSED VAPOR W/ H20, MKC IS LOOKING INTO VALVE LOCKS TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A LEAK COMING FROM ONE, FORTY-ONE LITER STEEL DRUM ON THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY FORTY-ONE LITERS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY FORKLIFT.  FORWARD AIR, INC. DISPATCHED SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF NABLETON, GEORGIA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES APPLIED FLOOR DRY AND AN ALKALI DETERGENT TO CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED CONCRETE DOCK FLOOR.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES PLACED THE IMPACTED FLOOR DRY AND DAMAGED DRUM INTO THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED TO SOLID WASTE TECHNOLOGIES IN AMERICUS, GEORGIA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL VIA LANDFILL.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

4-28-04 AWB 54566537373 RICCA CHEMICAL CO.  PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING AT STATION.  CONTACTED RESPONSE CO., UPON INSPECTION INNER-GLASS RECEPTACLE FOUND BROKEN DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING & BRACING OF INNER CONTENTS.

WHILE MOVING A STEEL DRUM WITH A DRUM DOLLY, IT WAS PIERCED WITH THE CHISEL POINT OF THE DRUM DOLLY.  WHILE THE DOCK WORKER WAS TURNING THE LEAKING DRUM OVER SOME OF THE MATERIAL SPLASHED ONTO HIS SHOE AND PERMEATED ONTO HIS FOOT.  DOCK WORKER WAS SENT FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT AND WAS RELEASED. THE DOCKWORKER DID NOT MISS ANY DAYS AWAY FROM WORK.

WHILE AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A CRACK ON THE ROLLING RING CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION FROM THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A OVERPACK AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DRIVER WOKE UP FROM TAKING HIS BREAK & DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF HIS TRAILER.  LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER & THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS PLACED IN THE SHOP.  AFTER ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO SIT OVERNIGHT WITH 40 LBS PRESSURE ON IT NO LEAKS WERE FOUND.  THIS TEST WAS DONE TWICE & WE NEVER FOUND A LEAK WHICH INDICATES AT SOME POINT, PRODUCT SOMEHOW GOT INTO THE INSULATION & STARTED LEAKING AT THE TRUCK STOP.  WE SUSPECT IT CAME FROM A LOOSE WASH OUT CAP.

WHILE ON THE CARRIER'S WAREHOUSE FLOOR, ONE DRUM WAS HIT WITH A FORKLIFT PLACING AN HOLE INTO THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SAFE TRANSIT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM.
SKID OF POOL ITEMS WAS SITTING ON FLOOR OF DOCK & A FORKLIFT HIT THE SKID & CRUSHED CARTON & 1 GALLON PAIL.  HALF OF CONTENT LEAKED OUT.

THE PALLET WAS SETTING ON THE DOCK BY THE DOCK STAND ALL DAY.  WHILE I WAS ON MY SHIFT IT WAS FINE.  SOME HAD HIT IT WITH A FORKLIFT DURING THE NIGHT. CAUSING DAMAGE TO ONE TWO GALLON JUGS.  CAUSING THE SPILL ON THE UPO DOCK.
column172: Jug, glass or plastic not specified, capacity more than 2 gallons and less than 5 gallons

column168: BNSF TRAIN DERAILED ITS THREE REAR CARS AFTER TRAVERSING A BROKEN (DETAIL FRACTURE) STOCK RAIL AT MAINLINE SWITCH.  SHPX206716 DERAILED, OVERTURNED & TOP PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER SHEARED-OFF.  PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE (VRV) THAT WAS UNABLE TO HOLD BACK LIQUID PRESSURE.  ALSO, MUD FORCED UNDER THE WEATHER CAP DEPRESSED VRV SPRING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  BNSF RESPONDERS CLEARED MUD FROM VRV, PRYING WEATHER CAP UP & VRV RESEATED, STOPPING PRODUCT RELEASE.  TANK CAR UPRIGHTED & REMAINING PRODUCT TO BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK CAR.  SPILLED PRODUCT THAT DIDN'T EVAPORATE WAS REMEDIATED.  COLORADO HIGHWAY PATROL EVACUATED THREE NEARBY HOUSEHOLDS.  ONE HOUSEHOLD WAS ALLOWED TO RETURN BY 0030 HRS.  MDT, WITH THE OTHER TWO BY 0230 HRS.  MDT ON 4/10.

GFSX 101238 IN RAILYARD REPORTED SPILLING PRODUCT FROM A-END BOTTOM OUTLET. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND BOTTOM OUTLET SLOPE SHEET CORNER SEAM HAD REMOVABLE TAPE PLACED OVER A CRACK NEAR SEAM & TAPE HAD LOOSENED.  ADDITIONAL TAPE APPLIED, ENDING RELEASE.  SPILLAGE ON GROUND REMEDIATED.  REMAINING PRODUCT TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER RAILCAR ON 4/29.  AFTERWARDS, SCALE WEIGHT INDICATED THAT A TOTAL OF 10950 LBS. POSSIBLY LOST ENROUTE.

MT, 4/24 (NO NEW 165 PSI DISC IN STOCK AT THAT TIME). ON 4/28, BNSF RESPONDER INSTALLED A NEW 165 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC ON UTLX 801638 & TANK CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO APA.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT DRIED ON TANK SHELL.

DRIVER CHECKED PRODUCT LEVEL IN TANK #10.  MEASUREMENT WAS 3'3".  HE READ IT AS HAVING 1,000 GALLONS.  HE UNLOADED 8,400 GALLONS.  TANK ACTUALLY HAS 1,900 GALLONS TO BEGIN WITH.  WHEN DRIVER BLEW BACK LINES, PRODUCT SPUTTERED OUT THE TOP OF THE TANK AND DOWN THE SIDE INTO THE TANK FARM.  A WAREHOUSEMAN QUICKLY DRUMMED OFF DRUMS OF PRODUCT.  THIRTY-FIVE GALLONS OF TOLUENE WAS RECOVERED FROM THE TANK FARM.  THE DRIVERS AND WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL WILL BE RETRAINED IN THE CORRECT RECEIVING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.  A CORRECTIVE AND PREVENTATIVE ACTION REQUEST (CAR) WAS WRITTEN UP FOR THE PARTIES INVOLVED AND FOLLOWED THROUGH WITH SUPERVISORS AND MANAGEMENT.

column168: ON APRIL 11, 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 2350 HOURS, A RAILWAY TANK CAR ACFX 71519 CONTAINING ETHANOL, 3, UN1170, PG II WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI YARD.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO A REMOTE TRACK FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND REPAIRS.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO THE SITE AND REPORTED THAT THE LEAK HAD ORIGINATED FROM THE BOTTOM FLANGE PLATE, WHICH IS BOLTED TO AND CONNECTS THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO THE CAR.  THE RESPONDER FIRST PLACED CONTAINERS UNDERNEATH THE TANK CAR TO CATCH THE LEAKAGE.  THE SHIPPER ARRIVED ON SITE THE FOLLOWING DAY REPAIRING THE CAR AND REMOVING THE SPILLED PRODUCT OFF SITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.

WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED AND FREIGHT MOVED.  THEY FOUND 1 PALLET STACKED ON TOP OF A PALLET OF 5 GALLONS PAILS OF ADHESIVE.  THEY FOUND 1 - 5 GAL PAIL MASHED AND LEAKING ONTO PIECES FROM THE SAME SHIPMENT.  REPORTS WERE MADE AND COPIES SENT TO DESIGNATED PERSONS AND ORIGINAL TERMINAL FOR TRAINING.  THE PALLET WAS IMPROPERLY LOADED, CAUSING THE DAMAGE TO THE 5 GAL PAIL.  THE PAIL WAS REPOURED AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.

column168: THE FREIGHT IN QUESTION WAS A BOX CONTAINING MAYBE 20-25 APPROX. .75 LITER BOTTLES OF EMBALMING FLUID.  STEVE DIONNE IS THE ASSOCIATE WHO MOVED THIS FREIGHT.  SOME OF THE TAPING WAS LOOSE SO WHEN STEVE LIFTED THE BOX TO STACK IT.  THE CONTENTS FELL OUT AND THE CAP BROKE ON ONE OF THE BOTTLES CAUSING THE EMBALMING FLUID TO SPLASH ON HIS HEAD AND NECK.  HAD STEVE TAPED THE BOX BEFORE LOADING IT, THIS MISHAP MOST LIKELY WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED.  AS FAR AS HIS INJURIES THEY HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY TREATED BY THE INITIAL AND SEVERAL FOLLOW-UP APPTS TO MEDICAL PROFESSIONALS.  THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED FOR CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF THE FLUID.

column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE DRUM SLIGHTLY LEAKING AFTER MAKING A PICKUP AT ANOTHER CUSTOMER.  THERE WERE SEVEN DRUMS NOSED LOADED INTO THE TRAILER. WHEN MAKING A PICKUP AT ANOTHER CUSTOMER HE NOTICED A DRUM SLIGHTLY LEAKING AFTER FREIGHT WAS LOADED BEHIND SAID DRUMS.  APPARENTLY THE FREIGHT LOADED BEHIND THE DRUMS SLIGHTLY PUNCTURED ONE OF THE STAGED CONTAINERS.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY FLIPPED OVER TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE AND SPILLED MATERIAL CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT.  DRUM WAS RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER IN A RECOVERY DRUM AS PER INSTRUCTED.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DUNNAGE OF SOME SORT WAS PLACED BETWEEN THE TWO SHIPMENTS.

WHEN STAGING PALLET OF SAID BAGS ON DOCK, FORKLIFT OPERATOR RUBBED AGAINST ANOTHER STAGED PALLET CONSEQUENTLY RIPPING TWO OF THE BAGS ON THE PALLET. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PUT INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER, AND TWO BAGS WERE TAPED AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY CONTAINER AND FORWARDED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF FORKLIFT OPERATOR PAID ATTENTION TO HIS CLEARANCES.

AS A COMPANY EMPLOYEE WAS WALKING ACROSS THE DOCK HE OBSERVED A PAIL THAT WAS STAGED ON THE DOCK SLIGHTLY LEAKING.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT SOMEONE HAD STRUCK IT WITH ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT THAT WAS STAGED BEHIND IT.  DAMAGED JUG WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH ABSORBENT USED TO CLEAN UP THE UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER FORKLIFT OPERATOR DISCOVER ONE BAG LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BAG HAD BEE PINCHED BY A PALLET THAT WAS STAGED IN FRONT OF IT WHEN IT WAS ORIGINALLY LOADED INTO THE TRAILER.  THIS PROBABLY COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DUNNAGE HAD BEEN USED IN BETWEEN THE TWO PALLETS.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED BAG AND RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  CALLED INTO NATIONAL SPILL RESPONSE CENTER PER 171.15 49CFR, INCIDENT NUMBER #718778.

THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF FORKLIFT OPERATOR PAID ATTENTION TO FORKBLADE CLEARANCES WHILE UNLOADING.

column168: WE WERE TRANSFERRING A 1,000-GALLON ASME BULK PROPANE TANK CONTAINING LESS THAN 5% FROM OUR JUPITER, FL LOCATION TO OUR PALM BAY, FL LOCATION.  OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN FROM MAPLEWOOD DRIVE ONTO INDIANTOWN ROAD, A.K.A. STATE HIGHWAY 706, IN JUPITER, FL, WHEN THE TANK SLID OUT FROM UNDER THE STRAPS SECURING IT TO THE FLATBED AND IT ROLLED ONTO THE ROADWAY. UPON ROLLING ON THE ROADWAY, THE TANK'S SERVICE VALVE WAS SHEERED OFF.  AT THIS TIME PROPANE STARTED TO ESCAPE FROM THE TANK.  WITHIN MINUTES THE MANAGERS FROM BOTH OUR LOCATIONS RESPONDED AND PLUGGED THE SHEERED VALVE PORT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND JUPITER POLICE SECURED THE AREA UNTIL THE TANK WAS RELOCATED TO OUR JUPITER LOCATION, WHERE THE REMAINING PROPANE WAS SECURED.  OUR FLATBED DRIVER WAS ISSUED A CITATION FOR AN UNSECURED LOAD FROM BOTH THE JUPITER POLICE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE OF FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  WE ARE REPORTING THIS INCIDENT DUE TO THE CLOSURE OF INDIANTOWN ROAD, A.K.A. STATE HIGHWAY 706, FOR 90 MINUTES.  TO HELP ENSURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN WE HAVE RETRAINED AND REPRIMANDED THE DRIVER.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT WHILE IT WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

THE DRIVER STAGED THE UNIT TO START THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE DRIVER CONNECTED THE OFF-LOADING HOSE TO THE DISCHARGE ON THE TRAILER AND OPENED THE DOME LID.  AT THAT TIME THE DRIVER NEEDED TO MOVE THE UNIT FORWARD AS THE OFF-LOADING LINE HAD A SLIGHT BEND IN IT.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE TOE DOME LID BEFORE MOVING THE UNIT.  APPROX. 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE DOME OPENING.  CTL SENT OUT A CLEAN UP CREW TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP.  ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO IMPERVIOUS SURFACE.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELLED ON PROPER SECUREMENT AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF TRAILER THE PLASTIC 55 GAL DRUM CAP SEEMED LOOSE, AND LEAKED WHILE ENROUTE TO SANTA FE SPRINGS, CA.  .25 OZ LEAKED ON TOP OF THE RIM OF THE DRUM.  THE CAPS SHOULD BE TIGHT SO NO FLUID LEAKS OUT.  I CALLED OUR SAFETY DEPARTMENT, THE SHIPPER, AND DISPOSAL COMPANY FOR ADVICE ON HOW TO HANDLE THE LEAKING FLUID FROM CAP AREA.

column58: Basic Material; Cylinder Sidewall - Near Base
column168: DPC WAS NOTIFIED BY THE CITY OF CLEARWATER THAT A CHLORINE CYLINDER WAS LEAKING AT THEIR RECREATION CENTER POOL.  DPC DISPATCHED AN EMPLOYEE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CUSTOMER SITE, THE CYLINDER HAD AUTO-REFRIGERATED AND THERE WAS NO APPARENT LEAK.  THE CYLINDER WAS LOADED INTO THE COMPANY PICK-UP TRUCK FOR TRANSPORTATION BACK TO DPC-TAMPA FACILITY.  WHILE IN TRANSIT, THE CYLINDER DEVELOPED A LEAK.  THE DPC DRIVER PULLED OFF THE HIGHWAY AND REQUESTED HAZMAT ASSISTANCE.  POLICE CLOSED THE HIGHWAY AND EVACUATED A NEARBY RESTAURANT.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVE AND PLACE THE CYLINDER INTO A CONTAINMENT VESSEL.  TO PREVENT AN INCIDENT SUCH AS THIS IN THE FUTURE, DPC IS DEVELOPING A PROCEDURE AND EQUIPMENT LIST FOR OFF-SITE CUSTOMER RESPONSES; ALL TAMPA EMPLOYEES WILL UNDERGO REFRESHER TRAINING ON DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS; AND APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINARY ACTION IS BEING TAKEN.

THE DRIVER FAILED TO HAVE HIS BLEEDER VALVE IN THE CLOSED POSITION WHEN THE TRAILER WAS OPENED.  THE BLEEDER VALVE ON THE TRACTOR PUMP WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION CAUSING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO IMPERVIOUS SURFACE.  THE CUSTOMER PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AND RE-TRAINED BY THE SAFETY DEPT. ON SPILL PREVENTION AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

THE DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK AT THE INTERNAL VALVE ASSEMBLY.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO UNLOAD THE CARGO TANK WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS.  THE CARGO TANK WAS DISPATCH INTO CTL MULBERRY, FL TERMINAL FOR REPAIRS.  REPAIRS WHERE COMPLETED AND THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE.

PICTURES #1 + 1-A SHOW THAT THE SAME SYSTEM IS USED TO LOAD THE RAIL AS WELL AS THE TRUCKS.  PICTURE #2 SHOWS A VALVE THAT DIRECTS THE ETHANOL TO WHICH EVER VEHICLE IS BEING LOADED.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO TURN THE VALVE TO THE TRUCK WHICH RESULTED IN THE PRODUCT GOING TO THE RAIL SIDE.  THE METER, START & STOP CONTROLS, ARE IN A SMALL BUILDING JUST TO THE EAST OF THE DIRECTIONAL VALVE.  THE PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT THE RAIL SPOUT WHICH HAD THE SHUT OFF PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT THE RAIL SPOUT WHICH HAD THE SHUT OFF VALVE TIED OPEN.  (PICTURE #3) WITH A SOUTH WIND, IT WAS SHOOTING ACROSS THE MAIL CAN SO HE DID NOT SEE IT.  I HAVE GONE OVER LOADING PROCEDURES WITH THE DRIVERS AND HAVE ASKED THE TERMINAL TO NOT TIE THE VALVE OPEN TO THE RAIL LOADING SIDE.  IF THE RAILING LOADING VALVE HAD NOT BEEN LEFT TIED OPEN, THIS WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED.
FORKS ON THE FORKLIFT MISSED THE SKID AND PUNCTURED THE PAIL.

AN OFFICE EMPLOYEE COMPLAINED OF RESPIRATORY PROBLEMS AND WAS ALSO CHECKED OUT BY A DOCTOR. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP AND ALL WASTE WILL BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

HE WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE TERMINAL MANAGER TO CALL THE POLICE DEPARTMENT.  AAG ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A VAPOR PROBLEM WAS WELL AS A DROP TUBE ISSUE WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SPILL.  THIS WAS INVESTIGATED AND DETERMINED TO BE A MAINTENANCE PROBLEM AND NOT CAUSED BY THE DRIVER.  AAG ENV. CLEANED UP ALL SPILL AND THERE IS NO ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES NOR WATER CONTAMINATION.

column168: AN EIGHTEEN WHEEL TRAILER-MOUNTED STAINLESS STEEL VACUUM TANKER (VACUUM TANKER) USED TO TRANSPORT THE WASTE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL OVERTURNED DURING A DELIVERY BY CIMA ON APRIL 23, 2004 AT 5:30AM.  A COPY OF THE WASTE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL ANALYTICAL IS ATTACHED TO THIS LETTER.  AS A RESULT OF THE TRUCK DRIVER GOING OFF THE ROAD INTO THE CENTER GRASS MEDIAN AND ATTEMPTING TO RETURN TO THE LEFT LANE OF I-30, THE VACUUM TANKER OVERTURNED ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE AND SLID ON THE HIGHWAY APPROXIMATELY 150 FEET BEFORE STOPPING ACROSS A PORTION OF THE GRASS MEDIAN TO BEYOND THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF I-30 JUST WEST OF THE CR3535 BRIDGE.  THE TRUCK DRIVER MANAGED TO EXIT THE TRACTOR THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD AND FLED THE SCENE BEFORE THREE SMALL EXPLOSIONS OCCURRED RESULTING FROM IGNITION OF THE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL AFTER THE VACUUM TANKER'S SCRUBBER BROKE OFF AND PENETRATED THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK WHEN IT OVERTURNED.  THE WASTE MANIFEST (MANIFEST DOCUMENT NUMBER AR1376964 ATTACHED TO THIS LETTER) INDICATED THAT 34,700 LBS (5,338.46 GALLONS) WAS ORIGINALLY LOADED INTO VACUUM TANKER.  A SIGNIFICANT PORTION OF THE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL WAS CONSUMED IN THE FIRE.  ALSO, THE TRUCK DRIVER MENTIONED THAT THE TRACTOR HAD APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLON OF DIESEL FUEL IN ITS FUEL TANKS AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT AND A SIGNIFICANT PORTION WAS CONSUMED AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE.  THE REMAINING ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL AND DIESEL FUEL RAN ON THE EAST SIDE OF I-30 AND MOVED INTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH AND SATURATED THE SOIL.  THE FIRST RESPONDER TO THE SPILL INCIDENT WAS THE HOPKINS COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT (HCFD) WHO SUPPRESSED THE FIRE WITH WATER. INITIAL REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES BY THE HCFD INCLUDED PLACEMENT OF ABSORBENT BOOMS ACROSS THE IMPACTED DRAINAGE DITCH AND ABSORBENT PADS UNDER THE VALVES AND HATCHES OF THE DAMAGED VACUUM TANKER TO ABSORB RESIDUAL ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL AND DIESEL FUEL.  OFFICER BRUCE ROBERTS OF THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY (DPS) NOTIFIED REID LAMB, WHO IS THE PRESIDENT OF CIMA, ABOUT INCIDENT AT 6:45 AM, APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR AND A HALF AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  OFFICER ROBERTS ALSO INDICATED THAT NO SERIOUS INJURIES HAD OCCURRED AS RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  AFTER BEING NOTIFIED, REID LAMB CONTACTED TEXAS INSTRUMENTS' ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT AS WELL AS JEFF WARD WHO IS CIMA'S WASTE SERVICES MANAGER.  EN ROUTE TO WEAVER, TEXAS, WHICH IS APPROXIMATELY 15 MILES EAST OF SULPHUR SPRINGS, TEXAS; REID LAMB CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AT 7:45 AM TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE RELEASE AND REID LAMB RECEIVED REFERENCE NO. 719655 FROM THE NRC.  THEN REID LAMB CONTACTED TO SET ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. TO ASSIST CIMA IN RESPONDING TO THE RELEASE OF WASTE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE OF GRAINCO FS WAS DELIVERING AN AGRICULTURAL EXEMPT NURSE TANK LOAD OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CONTAINING 1415 GALLONS BEHIND A PICK-UP TRUCK. THE LOAD WAS SCHEDULED TO BE DELIVERED TO ERIC RASMASSON WHEN THE TANK MADE SEVERAL SWERVES CAUSING THE DRAWBAR TO BREAK AND THE TANK AND RUNNING GEAR TO TIP OVER IN THE DITCH.  THE VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANK WAS BROKEN AND VAPOR WAS ESCAPING THE TANK.  THE TANK WAS ON IT'S SIDE AND THE PICKUP TRUCK AND EMPLOYEE WERE NOT AFFECTED.  THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO CONTACTED THE OPERATIONS MANAGER.  THE OPERATIONS MANAGER CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPT., SHERIFFS DEPT., IL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, NRC, GRUNDY COUNTY ESDA, AND THE ILLINOIS STATE DOT.  HE THEN MADE HIS WAY TO THE ACCIDENT SITE.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE PARTIES INVOLVED THAT DUE TO THE RURAL SETTING AND WIND SPEEDS IN THE 20-25 MPH RANGE THE VAPOR WOULD DISSIPATE QUICKLY AND NOT ENDANGER ANYONE.  AFTER THE VAPOR WAS FINISHED ESCAPING THE BROKEN VALVE, THE VALVE WAS REPLACED AND THE TANK WAS TURNED UPRIGHT.  THE TANK WAS THEN LOADED ON A TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED TO THE PLANT.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO ANY PROPERTY AND GROUND CLEANUP WAS UNNECESSARY.  (I HAVE ENCLOSED A COPY OF OUR PERMANENT SHIPPING DOCUMENT.)

column168: ON APRIL 23, 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM EMPLOYEES OF T/A TERMINALS WERE LOADING RAIL CAR PLMX 35205 WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE RAIL CAR WAS LOCATED ON THE TERMINAL SCALES AT THE LOADING RACK.  DURING LOADING OPERATIONS, THE TERMINAL MANAGER HEARD A POPPING OR RATTLING NOISE THAT SOUNDED LIKE A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE OPENING ON THE RAIL CAR.  THE PUMPS WERE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED TO SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT TO THE RAIL CAR. FROM ATOP THE RAILCAR, THE TERMINAL MANAGER COULD HEAR A VAPOR RELEASE SOUND COMING FROM BETWEEN THE TANK AND SHELL OF THE RAIL CAR.  HE DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE END OF THE RAIL CAR.  HE DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE END OF THE RAIL CAR.  THREE (3) OPERATORS BEGAN SPRAYING WATER ONTO THE RAILCAR ANYWHERE GAS COULD POSSIBLY LEAK OUT BETWEEN THE TANK AND THE SHELL.  FIRE HOSES WERE UTILIZED TO SPRAY WATER TOWARD THE AMMONIA VAPORS THAT WERE ESCAPING.  WATER SPRAY WAS CONTINUOUSLY APPLIED FROM SHORTLY AFTER DISCOVERY ON 4/23/04 UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM ON APRIL 25, 2004. AFTER WATER OPERATIONS CONCLUDED, RESPONDERS CONTINUED TO SMELL TRACE AMMONIA VAPOR DUE TO VAPOR THAT REMAINED IN THE INSULATION BETWEEN THE CAR AND SHELL.  THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TERMINAL PROPERTY.  THE ACCIDENTAL RELEASE RESULTED IN AN UNDETERMINED QUANTITY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA (AMMONIA VAPOR).  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY (IEMA) AND THE MORGAN COUNTY LEPC ON APRIL 23, 2004. FOLLOW-UP NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO IEMA AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON APRIL 26, 2004.  ALL OF THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS OFFLOADED BY 4:00 PM ON APRIL 25, 2004.  THE RAIL CAR WAS RETAINED ON TERMINAL PROPERTY.  ON APRIL 27, 2004 THE ILLINOIS DEPT. OF AGRICULTURE INSPECTED AND RED TAGGED THE RAIL CAR.  ON JUNE 8, 2004 A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE U.S. DEPT. OF TRANSPORTATION INSPECTED THE SUBJECT RAIL CAR (PLMX 35205) AND ARRANGED FOR THE RAIL CAR TO BE SHIPPED TO MILLENNIUM RAIL CAR (PLMX 35205) AND ARRANGED FOR THE RAIL CAR TO BE SHIPPED TO MILLENNIUM RAIL CAR SERVICE IN NEODESHA, KANSAS.  ALLTRANSTEK, LLC WAS CONTRACTED BY T/A TERMINALS TO PERFORM AN INVESTIGATION OF THE RELEASE.  THIS INVESTIGATION WAS PERFORMED ON JULY 1, 2004 AT THE MILLENNIUM FACILITY.  THIS INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF FAILURE TO BE RELATED TO THROUGH-WALL CORROSION.

TWO VEHICLES COLLIDED LEFT FRONT TO LEFT FRONT.  THE VEHICLES CONTINUED OFF THE ROADWAY, COMING TO A STOP ON THE EASTBOUND SHOULDER.  THE LEFT FRONT OF VEHICLE'S TWO'S TRAILER (OUR UNIT) WAS WHAT COLLIDED WITH VEHICLE ONE'S CAB.  THE DAMAGE TO OUR UNIT (VEHICLE 2) SHOWED THAT THE DRIVER DID AN EVASION ACTION TO TRY TO AVOID THE COLLISION.  DEBRIS FROM VEHICLE ONE, KNOCKED THE CYLINDERS OF AIR, COMPRESSED OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND SHEARED THE CYLINDER AND VALVES, LEADING TO RELEASE OF CONTENTS.  THE CYLINDERS WERE SECURED WITHIN THE VEHICLE UNDER CONDITIONS NORMALLY INCIDENT TO TRANSPORT.

column168: ACCORDING TO AN EYE WITNESS OUR DRIVER WAS FORCED OFF THE ROAD BY ANOTHER TRUCK.  OUR DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO RECOVER TO THE ROADWAY AND CAME INTO CONTACT WITH A ROCK WALL.  OUR TRUCK TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET IN CONTACT WITH THE ROCK WALL RIPPING OPEN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER WHICH RESULTED IN THE PRODUCT LOSS.  TPM, AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, HIRED BY KEYSTOPS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND PERFORMED THE REMEDIATION OF THIS INCIDENT.

ON APRIL 26, 2004 A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION WAS BEING MADE AT THE DELAWARE CITY POWER PLANT.  THE DELIVERY WAS BEING MADE BY THE KUEHNE CHEMICAL COMPANY THROUGH A PURCHASING AGREEMENT BETWEEN THE DELAWARE OPERATING SERVICES COMPANY AND THE GE BETZ COMPANY.  THE DELIVERY WAS BY TANK TRUCK AND WAS FOR A TOTAL OF 2500 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER UNLOADED INTO THE FACILITY WATER TREATMENT PLANT, BULK SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANK UNTIL THIS TANK WAS FULL.  THE TRUCK STILL HAD SOME PRODUCT IN IT AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PUT THIS INTO A SECOND TANK IN THE AREA.  THIS SECOND TANK WAS NOT FOR SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE BUT WAS FOR FERRIC SULFATE SOLUTION.  THE TWO SOLUTIONS ARE NOT COMPATIBLE AND THE ENSURING CHEMICAL REACTION EVOLVED OFF 21.8 POUNDS OF CHLORINE GAS.  AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE THE DNREC (DELAWARE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL) RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE CHLORINE GAS WAS DISPERSED THROUGH NATURAL DRAFT AND SOME FANS.  THERE WERE NO OFF SITE CONSEQUENCES.  THERE ARE TWO OPERATORS AT THE WATER TREATMENT PLANT WHO WERE EVACUATED AS A SAFETY PRECAUTION.  THE AREA EVACUATION WAS FROM 15:45 TO 18:45 ON THE 26TH.  THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR CHECK UP, EVALUATION AND WAS RELEASED WITH NO ILL EFFECTS FOUND.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION WAS ALSO OBSERVED IN THE TANK CONTAINMENT AREA (LESS THAN 5 GALLONS), WHICH WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND SUBSEQUENTLY CLEANED UP FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMERS, HOOKED UP HOSES AND BEGAN UNLOADING.  IN VIOLATION OF WRITTEN COMPANY POLICY AND PROCEDURES HE RETURNED TO HIS CAB AND APPARENTLY WENT TO SLEEP.  WHEN HE AWOKE HE THOUGHT HE HAD COMPLETED HIS UNLOADING, PUT THE TRUCK IN GEAR AND DROVE OFF, TEARING THE HOSE FROM ITS FITTINGS.  THE HARBOR POLICE NOTICED HE WAS LEAKING PRODUCT AND PULLED HIM OVER.  WE IMMEDIATELY BEGAN WORKING OUR EMERGENCY CONTINGENCY PLAN AND DISPERSED OUR OWN CLEAN UP TEAM AND CONTRACTED WITH OTHERS TO ASSIST US IN CLEANING UP THIS SPILL.  DRIVER HAD TREE PREVIOUS YEARS EXPERIENCE DOING THIS EXACT SAME TASK, AND HE HAD MORE THAN ADEQUATE EXPERIENCE AND TRAINING IN THIS OPERATION.  AFTER OUR CAREFUL INVESTIGATION WE COULD FIND NO MITIGATING REASONS FOR THIS INCIDENT TO HAVE OCCURRED.  AS A CONSEQUENCE THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.  THIS INCIDENT WAS PURELY CAUSED BY HUMAN ERROR.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII & VIII ABOVE: NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  OUR DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO MAKE A BULK DELIVERY OF #2 HEATING TO CUSTOMER'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  OUR DRIVER MISTAKENLY CONNECTED TO  THE CUSTOMER'S NO-LEAD GASOLINE TANK AND STARTED MAKING THE DELIVERY.  OUR DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE PRODUCT STOPPED FLOWING THROUGH THE HOSE AND STOPPED THE DELIVERY.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF GAS/FUEL MIX CAME OUT FROM AROUND THE FILL PIPE AND SPILLED ONTO THE BLACKTOP.  IT WAS RAINING HEAVILY WHICH CAUSED THE FUEL TO SPREAD OUT ONTO A WIDER AREA.  LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED, THEY EVALUATED THE SCENE WITH VAPOR TESTING EQUIPMENT AND FOUND NO CONCENTRATIONS.  LUZON OIL WAS CONTRACTED FOR CLEANUP AND THEY USED SOME PADS AND CLAY ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN OUT THE FILL PIPES.  THE GAS/ FUEL MIX IN THE UST WAS PUMPED OUT AND TAKEN TO REFINERY FOR DISPOSAL.  THE NYS DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED #04-00017 TO THIS INCIDENT.  CERTIFIED MAIL # 7003 2260 0001 2085 9410
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE THE DRIVER WAS FILLING A 275 GALLON INSIDE TANK WITH #2 HEATING OIL, A SPILL OF UNDER 1 GALLON OCCURRED THRU THE VENT TUBE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED.  THERE WAS NO RUN-OFF INTO ANY WATERWAYS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED A RUPTURED SEAM WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE UNDAMAGED PORTION OF THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

THE PAIL WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED.  EXAMINATION OF THE PAIL REVEALED THE PAIL HAD A LOOSE CAP/LID AND LEAKED.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE CAP/LID WAS SECURED.  UNDAMAGED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column168: THE DRY DEWAR ISN'T REGULATED UNLESS THERE IS A FREE-STAND LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE DEWAR.  THIS DEWAR WAS TRANSPORTED BACK FEDEX BY AIR FROM AIR FROM THE RECIPIENT TO THE SHIPPER AS UNREGULATED.  THE SHIPPER, DR. COOPER WAS TAKEN SEMEN STRAWS FROM THE DEWAR AND REPLACED THE STRAWS IN THE DEWAR AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO RETURN THE DEWAR WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER APPARENTLY FAIL TO DRAIN THE DEAR OF FREE-STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN, WE ACCIDENTLY TIPPED THE BOX OVER ALLOWING THE DEWAR TO VENT AS ITS' DESIGNED TO.  FEDEX EMPLOYEE REPORTED THEY SAW NOT ONLY VAPOR BUT ACTUAL LIQUID NITROGEN EXIT THE DEWAR.  TO VERIFY THAT I HAD TRICIA IEHLY POINT THE FLASHLIGHT BEAM INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE DEWAR. SHE GOT A REFLECTION THAT INDICATED TO ME THAT THERE WAS IN FACT LIQUID NITROGEN PRESENT.  I SPOKE TO ANNE AT THE DR'S OFFICE WHO VERIFIED THEY DID NOT RECHARGE THE EMPTY DEWAR, THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA GLORIA WILLIAMSON FROM THE ATL FAA VIA THE COMM CENTER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column168: CON-WAY DRIVER LEON MILTON WAS GOING TO HOOK TO TRL 313-0295 DESTINED FOR CARLSTADT, NJ FOR OUR DAYTIME LINEHAUL OPERATION WHEN HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THIS TRAILER WAS PUT INTO THE DOCK AND WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A DRUM LEAKING UP IN THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 INCH OF RESIN SOLUTION ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE MSDS SHEET FOR THE PRODUCT WAS FAXED TO THE TERMINAL.  IT WAS RECOMMENDED TO USE BREATHING APPARATUS IN THE CLEANUP OF THE PRODUCT SO WE THEN CONTACTED SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP.  THE DRUMS WERE LOADED ON THE TRAILER BY CON-WAY DRIVER TIM GREENE AND THERE WAS PLYWOOD ON ALL SIDES OF THE DRUMS.  PRO 472436613 WAS LOADED DIRECTLY BEHIND THE DRUMS BY CON-WAY DRIVER MITCH HORABIK.  THIS SHIPMENT CONSISTED 8 JOB BOXES WHICH WERE ONLY ABOUT 2-3 FEET LONG.  IT APPEARS THAT WHEN HE LOADED THE JOB BOXES, THAT THE FORKS SLID UNDERNEATH THE PLYWOOD AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THE INNER CONTAINERS SAID "CORROSIVE". IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY A CORROSIVE SINCE THE SHIPPER DID NOT OFFER THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS, LABELS, NOR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION.  FAA AGENT WENDY DENT-HENRY WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX HELD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HER INVESTIGATION.

column168: FILE 3512D, SHIPPER: RICHARD ALLAN SCIENTIFIC AWB# BTL 24183276364 NSH ON 04/02/04 ABX DRI ER SCOTT DUNCAN NOTICED A PURPLE LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF SHIPMENT AND HAD LEAKED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE VAN AND ONTO HIS PANT LEG AND HANDS.  HE ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER SHIPMENT, CONSIGNEE REFUSED SHIPMENT AND ADVISED SCOTT SHIPMENT WAS NOT EXPOSURE HARMFUL.  SHIPMENT WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE TRUCK AND RETURNED TO BOSTON NORTH SHORE STATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT STATION SCOTT REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO JIM CLIFFORD FSS DISPATCH, JIM REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO ABX AIR INC. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HOTLINE, AND TO MIKE TRUDEAU FSS AM.  ABX AIR INC. HAZMAT HOTLINE ADVISED TO ISOLATE TRUCK AND HAVE DRIVER REMOVE THE STAINED PANTS AND WASH THE EFFECTED AREA WITH SOAP AND WATER.  HOTLINE WOULD SEND IN A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO INVESTIGATE AND CLEAN UP SPILL.  FLEET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  THEY FOUND ONE FIBERBOARD BOX MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS.  BOTTOM OF THE BOX AND VAN HAD VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 1 GLASS BOTTLE X 1.95 LITERS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (ETHANOL) HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY .75 LITERS OF THE 1.95 LITERS BEING SHIPPED.  CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE IS UNKNOWN.  SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE VAN WAS CLEANED AND PUT BACK INTO SERVICE.  VAN DOWN TIME, 1.5 HOURS.  ALL DEBRIS FROM CLEAN UP WAS ALSO PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM.  SPILL TEAM CLEAR OF SCENE: 2030 THE ABOVE INFORMATION WAS REPORTED VIA EMAIL AND FAX TO HAZMAT HOTLINE BY MIKE TRUDEA AND JIM CLIFFORD.

NRC718185 IN SERC 2004-04-045 THINKING THAT ANOTHER ASSOCIATE HAD INDICATED THAT THE 1000 GAL. NURSE TANK WAS READY, ANOTHER ASSOCIATE PULLED THE NURSE TANK AWAY FROM THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA RISER WITH THE HOSES STILL CONNECTED. THE HOSES PULLED OFF THE RISER, RELEASING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM THE HOSES AND THE NURSE TANK VALVES.  THE MAJORITY OF THE AMMONIA DISSIPATED IN THE ATMOSPHERE.  A SMALL AMOUNT WENT ONTO THE GROUND, WHERE SITE ASSOCIATES USED A GARDEN HOSE TO DILUTE IT WITH 5-6 GALLONS OF WATER.  PET ABSORB WAS USED TO SOAK UP THE WATER AND THIS IS STORED ON CONCRETE ON SITE UNTIL IT CAN BE LAND APPLIED PER REQUEST OF IDEM.  THREE LOADS OF SOIL AND ROCK WHERE USED TO REPLACE THE EXCAVATED AREA AT A COST OF $600.  ALL ASSOCIATES HAVE BEEN RETRAINED IN PROPER ANHYDROUS AMMONIA LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: THE FREIGHT WAS SITTING SLANTED IN THE BACK OF THE LONG BOX, SO INSTRUCTED BOTH JAMES AND JENNIFER TO DOWN STACK THE SKID SO IT WOULD NOT GET DAMAGE BY THE FORKLIFT.  THERE WAS NO APPARENT SIGN OF ANY THING LEAKING OUT OF THE BOXES AT THAT TIME.  NEXT THING I KNOW IS JAMES CAME TO ME SAYING THAT THEIR WAS A SPILL WITH ONE OF THE BOXES.  DAN AND I THAN OPENED UP THE BOX AND COULD TELL THAT IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE SEAL OF THE JUG.  JENNIFER ENDED UP COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE MATERIAL THROUGH THE RESIDUE THAT WAS SOAKED INTO THE BOX, SHE WENT DOWN AND RINSED OFF HE ARM WITH SOAP AND WATER.  I CONTACTED JEFF TURNER AND TOLD HIM WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND HAD JENIFFER FILL OUT A STATEMENT OF INJURY.  I OFFERED AS WELL TO TAKE HER TO THE HOSPITAL AND SHE REFUSED.

FILE:  3569D-SHIPPER:  PRIORITY CARE, AWB# CHA 88888553410 NEW.  04/29/2004 A LAB PACK LEAKING ON THE INSIDE WAS REPORTED IN EXPRESS "A" LATERAL 33 IN A BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 146 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN LOREN LORENZO DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED, UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND A PLASTIC LAB PACK WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE INSIDE OF THE LAB PACK.  HE REMOVED THE LAB PACK FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND THIS LAB PACK TO CONTAIN SIX PLASTIC BAGS WITH SEVEN SPECIMEN CUP INSIDE WITH UNKNOWN CONTENTS.  THERE WAS VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE INSIDE OF THE LAB PACK.  THE PLASTIC BAG AND SPECIMEN CUP HAD UNSECURE CLOSURES AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 30 ML OF THE UNKNOWN LIQUID INSIDE THE LAB PACK.  THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OF THE UNKNOWN LIQUID TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE LAB PACK.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL OR SECONDARY PACKAGING USED AS REQUIRED BY 49 CFR 173.199.  THE AREA INVOLVED WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED WITH BLEACH BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN SEALED AND BAGGED THE LAB PACK IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION. CLEAR OF SCENE 0333.

FULL TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN WILLIAM HENDERSON DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THIS BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 1X1 GALLON METAL CAN OF "ACRY-TEXT CLEAR SEALER" PACKED IN PAPER PACKING MATERIAL.  THE CLOSURE ON THIS CAN WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE ON THE CAN CAME LOOSE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  THE FULL TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE:1130.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

ON APRIL 13, 2004, I ARRIVED AT THE BASF CORP, FREEPORT TEXAS TO DELIVER A TANK TRUCK OF TRIMETHYLAMINE ANHYDROUS.  I ARRIVED TO THE INSPECTION AREA AT 0745.  I WENT THROUGH THE INSPECTION AREA & ARRIVED AT THE GUARDHOUSE AT 0810 & THEN THE SCALES AT 0820.  I WAITED AT THE SCALES UNTIL APP. 0930 AND WAS THEN TOLD TO GO TO THE UNLOADING AREA.  I WAS MET AT THE UNLOADING BY TWO BASF EMPLOYEES (KEITH PRINCE & JEREMY VOGEL).  I GAVE ONE OF THEM MY PAPERWORK & HE WENT TO GET APPROVAL TO OFFLOAD.  AT THAT TIME, I HOOKED UP THE PTO SHAFT & THEN PUT ON MY PPE.  I WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER & REMOVE THE LOCK FROM THE DOORS.  I NOTICED THAT THE BLEED OFF VALVE ON THE VAPOR LINE WAS HALF OPEN & BOTH SCREWS GOING INTO THE BLEED OFF VALVES WERE OFF.  I THEN HOOKED UP THE VAPOR HOSE & SECURED THE BLEED OFF VALVE.  I THEN OPENED THE HANDLE TO RELEASE THE PRESSURE ON THE LIQUID LINE & HOOKED UP THE HOSE & THEN SECURED THE BLEED OFF VALVE.  I THEN ASKED THE OPERATOR WHAT HIS TANK PRESSURE WAS & HE SAID ABOUT 80 POUNDS.  I LOOKED AT MY PRESSURE GAUGE AND IT READ 40 LBS.  THE OPERATOR THEN OPENED HIS VAPOR VALUES AND I OPEN THE VALVES GOING TO THE COMPRESSOR ON BOTH LINES.  I THEN OPEN BOTH INTERNAL & EXTERNAL VAPOR VALVES TO EQUALIZE THE PRESSURE ON THE CUSTOMERS TANK & MY TRAILER.  AFTER EQUALIZING THE TANK & TRAILER, THE CUSTOMERS TANK READ APP 70 LBS & MY PRESSURE GAUGE READ APP 60 LBS.  THE CUSTOMER THEN OPENED UP HIS LIQUID VALVES TO HIS STORAGE TANK WHICH IS IN THEIR STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE.  I THEN ATTEMPTED TO OPEN UP MY EXTERNAL & INTERNAL VALVES TO GET FLOW.  I THEN TURN ON THE COMPRESSOR.  AT THAT TIME I CLOSED MY INTERNAL LIQUID VALVE TO INCREASE PRESSURE ON MY TRAILER.  AT THAT POINT, THE PRESSURE GAUGE READING SLOWLY STARTED RISING. THE OPERATOR & I DISCUSS TEN WHEN SHOULD WE OPEN MY VALVE & I BELIEVE I SAID ABOUT 80 POUNDS.  THAT WOULD GIVE US ABOUT 10 POUNDS DIFFERENCE.  WHEN THE PRESSURE GAUGE READ BETWEEN 80 AND 85 POUNDS, I WAS IN THE PROCESS OF OPENING UP THE INTERNAL VALVE WHEN THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WENT OFF.  THE OPERATORS IMMEDIATELY SECURED THEIR VALVES & I SECURED MY VALVES & THEN RAN TO THE FRONT OF THE TRUCK TO SECURE THE PTO SHAFT.  THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS OPEN FOR ABOUT 15-30 SECONDS.  THE OPERATORS THEN CALLED THEIR FOREMAN & BASF AT THAT TIME WENT INTO A EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT MODE.  BETWEEN 5 TO 8 PERSONNEL SHOWED UP AT THE UNLOADING RACK AND THE OPERATORS & I INFORM THEM WHAT HAD HAPPEN.  I EXPLAINED THE PSI SETTING ON THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, WHERE IT WAS LOCATED & THE READING ON THE PRESSURE GAUGE.  I THEN CALLED THE PENSACOLA TERMINAL & INFORM ERIC SCHAFFER WHAT HAS HAPPEN & TO GET VERIFICATION ON THE SETTING OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  AT THAT TIME, THE FOREMAN MOTIONED ME BACK TO THE TRUCK & TOLD ME SOMEBODY TAPPED THE PRESSURE GAUGE & THE NEEDLE WENT UP TO 125.  AFTER DISCUSSING WHAT WE SHOULD DO.  WE DECIDED TO TRY TO OFFLOAD THE TRAILER & KEEP AN EYE ON THE PRESSURE GAUGE.  WE REOPEN ALL OF THE VALVE

column168: AT 1214HRS ON 4-7-04, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT STRANG YARDMASTER REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 2074 LOCATED IN BOWL TRACK 2 WAS LEAKING.  MGR LERCH REQUESTED THAT RMCC MAKE SHIPPER CONTACT VIA CHEM-TREC.  ON INSPECTION, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE 3" LIQUID VALVE, WHICH WAS LOCATED UNDER THE COMBINATION HOUSING, AND RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT A RATE LESS THAN ONE PINT EVERY MINUTE.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, DAVID GHORMLEY, EMERGENCY RESPONSE MANAGER FOR ROHM & HAAS, ALSO RESPONDED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE 3 INCH LIQUID BALL VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS IN POSITION, NOT COMPLETELY WRENCH TIGHT.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY ONE TURN.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  MR GHORMLEY REQUESTED THE CAR BE RETURNED TO THEIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS NOR WATERWAYS IMPACTED FROM THIS RELEASE, NOR WERE THERE ANY REPORTED INJURIES.  THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP REQUIRED DUE TO PRODUCT EVAPORATING UPON COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.

BILL FEAR, ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CITY OF SALEM OREGON, REPORTED A SMALL LEAK FROM RAILCAR GATX 54891.  HE STATED SALEM FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS RESPONDING AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM UNION PACIFIC.  RICK SLOANE, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. OREGON STATE POLICE, OREGON DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, SERVICE INTERRUPTION, AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.  AT 05:49 PM SALEM FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUESTED TRAIN TRAFFIC IN THE AREA BE HALTED.  CASCADE CORRIDOR MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED, AND PROTECTION WAS PUT IN PLACE.  AMTRAK DESK, AMTRAK OPERATIONS, AMTRAK POLICE, AND BEN PEDERSEN, SENIOR MANAGER RMCC WERE NOTIFIED.  MGR. SLOANE DETERMINED THAT FOUR STUD NUTS SECURING THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WERE LOOSE.  MR. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON SUNDAY APRIL 18, 2004 AT ABOUT 0800 HOURS, GARY M. ARNDT, AN EMPLOYEE OF MINING SERVICES INTERNATIONAL, INC. (MSI), WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLLOVER ACCIDENT WHILE DRIVING A TRACTOR-TRAILER OWNED AND OPERATED BY MSI.  THE ACCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON A PUBLIC HIGHWAY AND RESULTED IN MINOR INJURIES TO MR. ARNDT, EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE TRACTOR-TRAILER, AND A SIGNIFICANT SPILL OF THE EMULSION THAT WAS IN THE TRAILER.  AN OFFICER OF THE WYOMING HIGHWAY PATROL, LOCAL FIRE AND RESCUE PERSONNEL, AND AN AMBULANCE FROM ROCK SPRINGS WYOMING RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  UPON ARRIVING AT BLACK BUTTE COAL COMPANY EARLY IN THE MORNING ON APRIL 18, 2004, GARY ARNDT WAS INFORMED THAT THE EMULSION STORAGE TANK IN THE PIT 8 AREA WAS EMPTY.  EMULSION WAS REQUIRED IN ORDER TO PROCEED WITH THE LOADING OF BLAST HOLES THAT WAS PLANNED FOR THE DAY SO MR. ARNDT DROVE HIS COMPANY VEHICLE TO THE MSI FACILITY AT POINT OF ROCKS, WYOMING.  AT THE PLANT MR. ARNDT FOUND A SEMI-TRACTOR (T-002) AND TRAILER (0012), LOADED WITH EMULSION AND PARKED ON THE TRUCK SCALE.  MR. ARNDT THEN STARTED THE RIG AND PROCEEDED TOWARD BLACK BUTTE COAL COMPANY WITH THE INTENTION OF PUMPING THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER INTO THE STORAGE SILO AT THE PIT 8 AREA, RETURNING THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TO THE PLANT, AND THEN GOING BACK TO THE MINE TO BEGIN LOADING OPERATIONS.  TRAVELING ROUGHLY EASTWARD ON THE BLACK BUTTE ROAD AT APPROXIMATELY 0800, MR. ARNDT ROUNDED A FAIRLY SHARP 90-DEGREE CURVE TO THE RIGHT, PASSED UNDER INTERSTATE 80, AND BEGAN TO NEGOTIATE A SECOND, SIMILARLY SHARP, CURVE TO THE RIGHT.  AT A POINT VERY CLOSE TO THE APEX OF THE CURVE, THE SEMI-TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE AND PULLED TRACTOR ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE AS WELL (THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER REMAINED COUPLED UNTIL THEY WERE STOOD UPRIGHT BY A TOW TRUCK AND UNCOUPLED BY THE WRECKER CREW). THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER SLID ACROSS THE OPPOSITE LANE (APPROXIMATELY 25-30 FEET), AND CAME TO REST WITH THE TRAILER IN A SHALLOW DITCH AT THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WITH EMULSION SPILLING ONTO THE GROUND FROM THE ACCESS COVERS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRACTOR WAS ALSO ON ITS SIDE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ONCOMING LANE OF TRAFFIC.  MR. ARNDT WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE TRACTOR BY CLIMBING OUT THROUGH THE PASSENGER SIDE DOOR (WHICH WAS, BY THEN, ON THE TOP OF THE TRACTOR).  HE THEN USED HIS CELL PHONE TO CALL FOR ASSISTANCE AND BEGIN MAKING NITIFICATIONS OF THE ACCIDENT.  LARRY LIPSEY, MSI TECHNICAL SERVICES REPRESENTATIVE AND MR. ARNDT'S SUPERVISOR, ARRIVED AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE AT ABOUT 0935.  MR. LIPSEY STATED THAT FOUND MR. ARNDT TALKING TO OFFICER KITCHNER OF THE WYOMING HIGHWAY PATROL.  MR. LIPSEY PROVIDED OFFICER KITCHNER WITH THE NECESSARY INSURANCE INFORMATION AND ANSWERED OTHER QUESTIONS AS THEY CAME UP.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL ISSUED MR. ARNDT A CITATION FOR "FAILURE TO MAINTAIN A SINGLE LANE" IN VIOLATION OF WYOMING STATUTE 31-5-209(A).  FIRE AND RESCUE PERSONNEL FROM THE SWEETWATER COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ON THE SCENE AND MR. LIPSEY PROVIDED THEM WITH THE INFORMATIO

NRC/CERCLA# 719792.  THE OUTLET VALVE BEGAN TO LEAK WHEN THE CUSTOMER ATTEMPTED TO TAKE OFF THE DUST CAP, AND THE VALVE HAD NOT YET BEEN OPENED. THIS WAS A NEW VALVE JUST INSTALLED ON THIS TANK IN DECEMBER 2003. APPROXIMATELY 1,312 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE AIR.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED IN THE CUSTOMER'S FIELD NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF BRAUN AND CLINTON-MANCHESTER RDS, BRIDGEWATER TOWNSHIP, WASHTENAW COUNTY, MICHIGAN.  THE TECUMSEH FARMARKET MANAGER WAS CALLED TO THE SITE AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE DUST CAP BUT WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL.  DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK AND THE WEATHER AT THE TIME IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE SAFEST OPTION WAS TO LET THE TANK CONTINUE TO BLEED OFF, AS THE LEAK WAS NOT LARGE IN NATURE, AS THERE WAS NO HARM TO ANY BODY OR TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  WHEN CHECKED ON MID-DAY 5/25 IT HAD QUIT LEAKING.  MONDAY, 5/26 THE TANK WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE TECUMSEH FARMARKET AND TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL IT CAN BE REPAIRED.

column168: BRIAN, YARDMASTER, ADVISED RAIL CAR SAUX 807 WAS VENTING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT THE PROVISO RAIL YARD.  LEE HAMMOND, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED,  MANAGER HAMMOND CONTRACTED WITH SET ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND.  HANDLING OF THE INCIDENT WAS TURNED OVER TO LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY.  MR. SEKAVEC ADVISED THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND CTEH HAD BEEN CONTACTED DUE TO THE POSSIBLE EXPOSURE OF AN EMPLOYEE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER AND HIS CONTRACTOR (HMHTTC) TO TRANSLOAD PRODUCT ON TRUCK ON SUNDAY, APRIL 18, 2004.  MARK MADAY, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED THAT ON MONDAY, APRIL 19TH, THE SHIPPERS CONTRACTOR (HMHTTC) STARTED THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING PRODUCT OUT OF THE LEAKING CAR.  THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED ON MONDAY, AND FINAL PURGING OF THE CAR WAS COMPLETED ON WEDNESDAY, APRIL 21. THE SHIPPER, TERRA NITROGEN, SUBMITTED THE MOVEMENT AUTHORITY REQUEST TO THE FRA THE SAME DAY.  APPROVAL WAS RECEIVED FROM THE FRA TO MOVE THE CAR ON MONDAY, APRIL 26TH.  ANN ABRAMS, FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR, INSPECTED THE CAR ON TUESDAY APRIL 27TH AND TOOK EXCEPTION TO THE CAR.  MR. MADAY REPORTED THAT BETWEEN APRIL 21-26, THE RESIDUE IN THE CAR HAD RE-VAPORIZED AND REPRESSURED THE CAR CAUSING THE LEAK TO RESUME.  MR. MADAY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND REQUESTED THAT THEIR CONTRACTOR COME BACK OUT AND RE-PURGE THE CAR.  TERRA NITROGEN HAD HMHTTC RETURN ON MONDAY, MAY 3RD.  MR. MADAY REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS REPURGED ON MONDAY, MAY 3RD, AND LEFT THE PROVISO YARD ON TUESDAY, MAY 4TH FOR THE SHIPPERS REPAIR FACILITY.

MARK MADAY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED TANKCAR PATU 440933 WAS LEAKING AT THE GLOBAL ONE YARD IN CHICAGO, IL.  MR. MADAY CONTRACTED WITH SET ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND.  AT 04:35 PM, MANAGER MADAY REPORTED ONE FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM OF RESIN HAD RUPTURED AND THE PRODUCT HAD JELLED OVER INSIDE THE CONTAINER, WITH NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 5:51 PM, MANAGER MADAY ADVISED HE SPOKE WITH THE SHIPPER, ASHLAND CHEMICAL, THEY AGREED UPON CLEAN-UP OF THE RELEASE.  ASHLAND PROVIDED A CONTACT TO COORDINATE THE DISPOSAL/RETURN OF THE DAMAGED DRUM AND CONTAMINATED CLEAN-UP MATERIALS.  AT 8:50 PM, MADAY REPORTED THAT A SECOND DRUM WAS LEAKING PRODUCT.  THE LEAKS WERE "PIN HOLE" IN SIZE, AND SHOW NO EVIDENCE THAT THEY WERE CAUSED BY RUBBING OR CONTACT WITH OTHER DRUMS.  MR. MADAY ALSO STATED THAT FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE ADDITIONAL DRUMS RAISED CONCERN THAT MORE DRUMS IN THE LOAD COULD BE LEAKING.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO "TRANS-LOAD" THE CONTAINER AND INSPECT THE REMAINING 78 DRUMS IN THE LOAD. THE CONTAINER PATU 440933 WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIN MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED.  MR. MADAY STATED THAT AFTER INSPECTING APPROXIMATELY 18 OF THE 78 REMAINING DRUMS, NO ADDITIONAL LEAKS HAD BEEN FOUND.  IN AN EFFORT TO EXPEDITE THE CLEAN-UP AND RELEASE OF THE REMAINING SHIPMENT, MR MADAY AND SET ENVIRONMENTAL DETERMINED THAT THEY COULD RECONFIGURE THE REMAINING LOAD IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, CLEAN-UP THE SPILLED RESIN SOLUTION FROM THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER, AND RELOAD AND SECURE THE SHIPMENT IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FASTER THAN "TRANS-LOADING" TO A NEW CONTAINER.  ALL REMAINING DRUMS IN THE CONTAINER WERE INSPECTED DURING THE RECONFIGURATION OF THE LOAD.  NO ADDITIONAL LEAKS WERE FOUND IN THE 78 REMAINING DRUMS.  ASHLAND CHEMICAL (THE SHIPPER) HAD ASHLAND ENVIRONMENTAL ARRANGE THE PICK-UP OF THE TWO (2) "OVERPACKED" LEAKERS AND THE TWO (2) DRUMS OF WASTE MATERIAL.  ASHLAND ENVIRONMENTAL HIRED SET ENVIRONMENTAL TO HANDLE THESE DRUMS.  THE CONTAINER WAS BEEN RELEASED TO THE RAMP FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT.

INVESTIGATION REVEALED A LEAK BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND THE FRANGIBLE DISC HOUSING.  ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE FLANGE BOLTS WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER (DYNO NOBEL) AND IT WAS DECIDED THEY WOULD SEND A CREW OUT TO ATTEMPT REPAIRS.  ON APRIL, 29, PERSONNEL FROM DYNO NOBEL ATTEMPTED TO REPAIR THE CAR WITHOUT SUCCESS.  A DECISION WAS MADE BY LARS STORY (DYNO NOBEL SUPERINTENDENT) TO RETURN THE TANK CAR TO THE PLANT, UNLOAD IT AND PERFORM THE REPAIRS THERE. THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE DYNO NOBEL PLANT AT WYCON, WY, FOR REPAIRS AND SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

STEVE, MANAGER TRACK OPERATIONS, REPORTED A STRONG SMELL OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANKCAR PLMX 2506 IN THE SETTEGAST YARD. TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, REGIONAL CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 3:23 AM. TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, REGIONAL CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED THE TANKCAR HAD A DEFECTIVE GAUGING DEVICE (LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT, OPEN VALVE, LOOSE PLUG, AND VALVE BODY NOT SECURED TO GAUGING DEVICE ROD). THE SHIPPER (NECHES WAS NOT REGISTERED WITH CHEMTREC AND COULD NOT BE REACHED. ATTEMPTS TO CONTACT CONSIGNEE (APACHE NITROGEN PRODUCTS) WERE MADE BUT UNSUCCESSFUL. AT 08:30 AM, MANAGER O'BRIEN ADVISED THE LEAK WAS SIGNIFICANTLY REDUCED AND THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED PART TO THE YARD. ON 04/03/2004, AT 04:26 AM O'BRIEN REPORTED THAT THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN TRANSLOADED INTO TRUCKS. THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAR WAS TAKEN DOWN TO ZERO. RESCAR, A CONTRACTOR, WOULD MAKE REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR PRIOR TO IT BEING RELEASED.

ON APRIL 29TH, 2004 SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT ATTENDANTS WERE MADE AWARE OF AN ODOR IN THE CABIN OF FLIGHT 1050 FROM BALTIMORE WASHINGTON INTERNATIONAL (BWI) TO CHICAGO MIDWAY AIRPORT (MDW).  THE LEAD FLIGHT ATTENDANT IDENTIFIED A BAG THAT WAS STORED IN THE OVERHEAD BIN AND INVESTIGATED TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE STRONG SOLVENT ("NAIL POLISH REMOVER") SMELL. A SINGLE 4-OUNCE CONTAINER OF SWAN GUM TURPENTINE HAD LEAKED IN THE CARRYON BAG AND WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  THE FLIGHT ATTENDANT AND FEDERAL AIR MARSHALS THAT WERE ONBOARD THE FLIGHT QUESTIONED THE CUSTOMER AND SECURED THE LEAKING FLUID IN A PLASTIC BAG TO MINIMIZE VAPORS.  THE FLIGHT CONTINUED TO CHICAGO MIDWAY WHERE THE CUSTOMER AND HER BAGGAGE WERE REMOVED FROM THE FLIGHT AND SHE WAS QUESTIONED FURTHER.  HER BAGS WERE TAKEN TO THE BAGGAGE SCREENING TO IDENTIFY FURTHER UNDECLARED MATERIALS.  AN ADDITIONAL BOTTLE OF TURPENTINE AND 2 BOTTLES OF RUBBING ALCOHOL WERE DISCOVERED IN THE CARRYON BAG.  SINCE THE CUSTOMERS FINAL DESTINATION WAS DETROIT (DTW), THE MDW STATION HELD THE CHEMICALS, TRANSFERRED NON CONTAMINATED MATERIALS TO ANOTHER BAG AND ALLOWED THE CUSTOMER TO PROCEED TO DTW.  THE MDW STATION CONTACTED THE LOCAL FAA DANGEROUS GOODS OFFICE TO INFORM THEM OF THE INCIDENT.  THE CUSTOMER CLAIMS THAT THE PRODUCT ARE MEDICINAL IN NATURE AND WAS UNCOOPERATIVE DURING HER QUESTIONING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: FRIDAY APRIL 9TH, 2004 I WAS NOTIFIED BY BILLY PUCKETT, FUEL DISPATCHER AROUND 11:45 A.M., THAT KEVIN DUNN, TANK WAGON DRIVER OF TRUCK #2308 HAD A REGULAR UNLEADED GASOLINE RELEASE AT ALABAMA POWER'S, FORRESTRY SITE, 731 WASHINGTON VALLEY ROAD, SPRINGVILLE, ALABAMA SAINT CLAIR COUNTY.  KEVIN WAS TO UNLOAD AT NEW TANK SITE ABOVE; HE CHECKED FITTINGS AND PLUGS IN EACH END OF TANK BEFORE STARTING HIS UNLOADING OF PRODUCT.  WHEN HE STARTED PUMPING OFF HE NOTICED GASOLINE ESCAPING FROM UNDERNEATH THE TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY REVERSED HIS PUMP AND CHECKED THE SITE.  HE CALLED BILLY PUCKETT AND MR. DENNIS WALTRIP SITE MANAGER FOR ALABAMA POWER.  BILLY PUCKETT IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED JODY HIGHTOWER OF TPE AND BOB RUTLEDGE.  JODY IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED BILLY TOLBERT AND SAM HOVIES TO THE SITE FOR IMMEDIATE EVALUATION.  ONCE BILLY, JODY, AND BOB HAD TIME TO GET TOGETHER, BOB RUTLEDGE NOTIFIED ADEM IN MONTGOMERY AND CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE LINE. RODNEY PRICE, MOP SALES REPRESENTATIVE WAS NOTIFIED.  BILLY TOLBERT ESTIMATED APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF GASOLINE HAD BEEN DISCHARGED THROUGH A DRAIN PLUG INSTALLED BY MANUFACTURER IN THE BOTTOM OF THE NEW TANK.  THE GASOLINE WAS CONTAINED AROUND TANK AND THERE WAS NO DANGER OF RUN OFF TO STREAM OR WATER SOURCES.  THIS TANK WAS RECENTLY PURCHASED FROM A NEW TANK SUPPLIER AND THE TANKS WE HAD BEEN PURCHASING ONLY HAD DRAIN PLUGS FROM A NEW TANK SUPPLIER AND THE TANKS WE HAD BEEN PURCHASING ONLY HAD DRAIN PLUGS IN THE ENDS.  THEREFORE, OUR TECHNICIANS DID NOT KNOW TO CHECK FOR A DRAIN IN BOTTOM MIDDLE OF THE NEW TANKS.  KEVIN DUNN COULD NOT HAVE SEEN THIS FROM HIS INSPECTION.  JODY AND BOB FELT THE BEST ACTION WAS TO REMOVE AGGREGATE AROUND TANK AREA AND CARRY IT TO OUR SITE IN TRUSSVILLE AND PLACE IT ON PLASTIC AND TREAT IT WITH GATOR ABSORBENT.  JODY DISPATCHED LOCAL CONTRACTOR WITH BACKHOE AND DUMP TRUCK TO THE SITE.  BOB WAS CALLED BY, MR. DARREN HOLLIMAN OUT OF BIRMINGHAM ADEM OFFICE, WHOM WAS THE DESIGNATED ADEM RESPONDER.  AFTER BOB AND MR HOLLIMAN DISCUSSED, MR. HOLLIMAN DECIDED HE WOULD VISIT THE SITE AND ADVISE ANY FURTHER ACTIONS NEEDED.  RODNEY PRICE ALSO INSPECTED THE SITE AND MET WITH MR. WALTRIP.  BOB RUTLEDGED CALLED, MR DENNIS WALTRIP WITH ALABAMA POWER TO ADVISE HIM OF INCIDENT STATUS AND STEPS WE WERE TAKING.  HE SEEMED TO BE FINE WITH OUR RESPONSE.  CONTRACTOR REMOVED AGGREGATE AND SOIL AROUND TANK AND SPREAD FRESH AGGREGATE AROUND CUSTOMER TANK.  IN THE MEANTIME, BILLY TOLBERT HAD INSTALLED PLUG IN TANK. JODY HIGHTOWER INSPECTED ALL OF THE NEW TANKS WE HAD RECENTLY RECEIVED AND FOUND THEY ALL HAD DRAINS IN THE SAME PLACE.  WHEN THE MATERIAL FROM SITE WAS DELIVERED TO TRUSSVILLE YARD, JODY HIGHTOWER INSPECTED AND SUPERVISED UNLOADING.  RODNEY PRICE FOLLOWED UP WITH CUSTOMER ON MONDAY, APRIL 12, 2004 AND CUSTOMER SEEMED TO BE SATISFIED.  BOB RUTLEDGE CALLED DARREN HOLLIMAN, ON MONDAY, APRIL 12, 2004, AND MADE SURE LOCAL ADEM OFFICE WAS HAPPY WITH OUR RESPONSE.  MR. HOLLIMAN STATED OUR RESPONSE AND
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON APRIL 16, 2004 AT 2002 MACK OWNED BY CLARK OIL CO. INC, DRIVER BY MARK E WILCOX RAN OFF THE ROADWAY AND STRUCK A TREE CAUSING A GAS SPILL.  THE TANKER AND TRACTOR BOTH WERE OVERTURNED TO ONE SIDE, SPILLING APPX. 1600 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  MS HIGHWAY DEPT. OF TRANSPORTATION, LOCAL FIRE DEPT. AND OTHER HIGHWAY PERSONNEL WERE ON THE SCENE.
